GoodNet — Licensing
====================

The platform consists of the kernel and the SDK. The kernel is GPL-2.0
with a Linking Exception that releases the plugin boundary from
copyleft propagation; the SDK is MIT. Plugins are independent builds
and may carry any license — including proprietary — provided they
interface with the kernel only through the stable C ABI defined in the
SDK.


Platform Components
-------------------

  Kernel  (core/, plugins/protocols/gnet/)
                                     GNU GPL-2.0 with Linking Exception
                                     →  core/LICENSE
                                     →  plugins/protocols/gnet/LICENSE

  SDK     (sdk/, public headers)     MIT License
                                     →  sdk/LICENSE


Linking Exception (summary)
---------------------------

The full text lives in `core/LICENSE` and is part of the kernel's
license. In one sentence:

  Plugins that interface with the kernel only through `gn_plugin_descriptor`,
  the five plugin entry points, and the vtable types declared in public
  `sdk/` headers are not derivative works of the kernel — they may be
  licensed under any terms (MIT, BSD, Apache 2.0, proprietary, …) and
  linked statically or dynamically.

What the exception does NOT cover:

  - Modifications to the kernel itself (sources under `core/` and the
    mandatory mesh-framing under `plugins/protocols/gnet/`). A modified
    kernel must be redistributed under GPL-2.0.
  - Plugins that reach past the SDK and reference internal kernel
    symbols or `core/` headers directly. Such code is a derivative
    work of the kernel and inherits GPL-2.0.

The rationale: the kernel itself stays free in the strong sense, while
the plugin layer is open to any business model — open-source ecosystem,
commercial dual-license, embedded proprietary differentiation. This is
the OpenJDK GPL-with-Classpath-Exception model, written explicitly so
the legal status that Linux has lived with as a "gray area" for thirty
years is unambiguous here.


Plugins
-------

Plugins are independent builds. Each carries its own LICENSE file in
its directory. The Linking Exception above means any license is
permitted, statically or dynamically linked.

In-tree convention for the bundled plugins shipped in this repository:

  - Reference / template / debug providers
    (null, raw, ...)               .. MIT License
  - Common transports
    (tcp, udp)                     .. MIT License
  - Real implementations with
    original work and no obvious
    upstream analogues
    (noise, ipc, heartbeat, ...)   .. Apache 2.0 License

These are conventions for the bundled tree. Out-of-tree plugins choose
freely.

The mandatory mesh-framing plugin under `plugins/protocols/gnet/` is
GPL-2.0 with the same Linking Exception as the kernel: it is
structurally part of the kernel binary and shares the kernel's
copyleft, while still permitting independent plugins to link
statically through the SDK.


